pporting paper (author, year) in its \"reasoning\" field.\n5. Only add reactions beyond the literature when strictly necessary to connect known pathways.\n6. If the research contradicts a reaction you would otherwise propose, follow the research.\n\n\nPREVIOUS FAILED ATTEMPTS - Learn from this feedback:\n============================================================\n\nAttempt 1:\n- Confidence: 0.82\n- Feedback: Overall, this is a strong and mostly well-connected histidine synthesis network centered on the correct literature core: Shen's erythrose/formamidine to imidazole-4-acetaldehyde chemistry followed by Strecker conversion to histidine. Network topology is good: 20 molecule nodes and 16 reaction nodes exceed the minimum, the graph is connected, and the designated hubs are chemically meaningful. Convergence is also good, especially at erythrose, imidazole-4-glycol, and imidazole-4-acetaldehyde. Environmental interconnection is present and mostly coherent, with hydrothermal C1 chemistry feeding surface sugar chemistry and surface products feeding biochemical assembly/preservation. The main limitations are chemical support for speculative connectors. In particular, hydrothermal formaldehyde generation from formate and the hydrothermal dehydration/oxidation funnel from imidazole-4-glycol or imidazole-4-ethanol to imidazole-4-acetaldehyde are not firmly demonstrated in the histidine literature, and formamidine availability remains a known bottleneck under dilute prebiotic conditions. The phosphoro-Strecker branch is a thoughtful way to address pH mismatch, but it is only indirectly supported because the neutral-pH phosphorylation-assisted Strecker chemistry has not been shown specifically for imidazole-4-acetaldehyde. A further formal issue is that the network description does not provide per-reaction literature citations and detailed conditions/mineral-agent specification as required by the generation schema, so literature alignment must be judged from the textual summary rather than fully documented reaction metadata. Despite these issues, the network does achieve histidine through experimentally supported final steps and includes explicit acknowledgment of open questions, making it acceptable overall.\n- Issues: ['Plausible as a systems-level variant, but the dehydration/oxidation funnel is the least secure step. Shen discussed dehydration of imidazole-4-glycol and possible oxidation of related alcohols, but direct hydrothermal mineral-catalyzed conversion using the proposed settings is not experimentally established in the histidine literature. This pathway reaches the target, but the key connector is speculative.', 'The alternate Shen branch via erythrose + formaldehyde + ammonia is literature-grounded, but this pathway depends on two uncertain connectors: hydrothermal generation of formaldehyde from formate and conversion of imidazole-4-ethanol/glycol to the aldehyde. The core histidine logic is coherent, yet the network overstates confidence in upstream hydrothermal formaldehyde chemistry relative to the cited histidine literature.', 'Reasonable as a convergent branch, but too much weight is placed on formaldehyde and the imidazole alcohol/glycol funnel, both of which are less securely demonstrated than the canonical formamidine route. The pathway is connected and reaches histidine, but key steps remain under-supported experimentally.', 'This pathway smartly addresses the pH mismatch between Shen condensation and classic Strecker by invoking neutral-pH phosphoro-Strecker chemistry, consistent with Ashe et al. (2019) in concept. However, that chemistry has not been validated for imidazole-4-acetaldehyde or for histidine-specific downstream hydrolysis/dephosphorylation. Thus it is a good hypothesis-driven extension, but not yet strongly literature-supported for this target.', 'This combines multiple low-confidence elements: uncertain hydrothermal formaldehyde generation, uncertain oxidation/dehydration to the aldehyde, and an unvalidated phosphoro-Strecker application to the histidine precursor. Although conceptually interesting, too many speculative steps accumulate for approval.', 'The staged redox-funnel concept addresses an open problem highlighted in the literature, but the hydrothermal execution is not directly demonstrated and may expose sensitive imidazole intermediates to destructive conditions. Good systems chemistry logic, insufficient direct validation.']\n\nAttempt 2:\n- Confidence: 0.81\n- Feedback: Overall, this is a good and mostly literature-grounded synthesis network with a strong central core for histidine production. Its greatest strength is that it correctly centers the Shen route as the main experimentally supported path: erythrose plus formamidine gives imidazole-4-acetaldehyde/imidzole-4-glycol under near-neutral warm conditions, followed by Strecker chemistry to histidine aminonitrile and hydrolysis to histidine. The network also does a good job identifying real hub molecules and convergence around erythrose, imidazole-4-glycol, imidazole-4-acetaldehyde, HCN, and histidine aminonitrile. Topologically, it is connected, has sufficient density, and shows plausible Hydrothermal to Surface to Biochemical progression. The main issues are chemical overreach in some feeder and alternative pathways. In particular, the formate plus ammonia to HCN/formaldehyde step is not well supported by the provided literature and weakens several pathways. Formamidine generation is acknowledged in the literature as a bottleneck, yet here it is treated too simply. The phosphoro-Strecker branch is reasonable as a speculative reconciliation of pH constraints, but it is not validated for the imidazole aldehyde substrate and appears to use phosphate rather than the better-supported diamidophosphate chemistry. The discharge-based direct histidine node is too strong a claim for what is really a complex-mixture observational result. Another concern is schema compliance: the summary omits whether every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction actually specifies required mineral agents; if the underlying JSON lacked them, that would be a significant formal defect. Even with these caveats, the network succeeds on target achievement and overall pathway coherence because the core histidine route is credible and literature aligned.\n- Issues: ['The HCN-to-sugars feeder is directionally consistent with Ritson-Sutherland style upstream chemistry, and aldol buildup to erythrose is plausible. However, the explicit step converting formate plus ammonia into both HCN and formaldehyde is not a literature-grounded or chemically clean prebiotic transformation as stated. The later Shen core remains strong, but this feeder route weakens confidence.', 'The network logic is good, but this pathway inherits the major weakness of rxn_002 and the moderate uncertainty of rxn_008. Hydrothermal carbon fixation is plausible, but the bridge from formate to the required cyanide/formaldehyde pool is not convincingly supported as drawn. The formaldehyde-ammonia branch is better than the feeder chemistry feeding it.', 'The neutral-pH phosphoro-Strecker concept is chemically motivated by Ashe et al. and does address the pH mismatch between Shen condensation and Strecker chemistry. However, the specific application to imidazole-4-acetaldehyde is not experimentally demonstrated in the literature provided, and the use of phosphate rather than diamidophosphate weakens alignment further. This is a reasonable speculative extension, but not strongly validated.', 'This combines two weakly supported components: the problematic reduced-C1 to HCN/formaldehyde feeder and the speculative phosphoro-Strecker finish. While the pathway is graph-theoretically coherent, it is not as literature-secure as the canonical Shen route and would need stronger mechanistic support to be convincing.', 'This pathway has attractive environmental interconnection, but the chemistry is dragged down by the same two major uncertainties: nonstandard formate-to-HCN/formaldehyde feeding and speculative neutral-pH phosphoro-Strecker implementation. Hydrothermal formate production itself is plausible, but the target-forming sequence is less secure than in P1 or P4.', 'This route has a plausible Shen-related feeder through imidazole-4-glycol, but pairs it with a speculative phosphoro-Strecker endpoint. The pathway is coherent, yet the two least secure steps are both central here, so confidence stays below approval.', 'This direct one-step route is the weakest element in the network. Although discharge experiments have reported histidine among complex products, they do not establish a clean direct conversion from HCN, ammonia, and formaldehyde to histidine in a mechanistically defined single-step pathway. Treating this as a direct biochemical node overstates the literature. It should remain only a highly speculative side observation, not a pathway.']\n\n============================================================\nAddress the above issues in your new network. Do NOT repeat the same mistakes.\n", "raw_response": "{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"Histidine\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"The network is centered on the experimentally demonstrated Shen histidine route: erythrose plus formamidine generates a small family of imidazole-functionalized C2 side-chain intermediates, with imidazole-4-acetaldehyde as the key branching hub; this aldehyde then undergoes Strecker-type conversion with HCN and ammonia to histidine precursors and finally histidine. To satisfy network completeness while remaining literature-grounded, upstream hydrothermal chemistry is limited to well-supported generation of formate and simple carbonyl feedstocks that can be transported into surface settings, and surface chemistry follows literature-supported HCN photoredox sugar formation, borate-stabilized aldol buildup to erythrose, and Shen's warm near-neutral imidazole chemistry. Multiple pathways to histidine are therefore generated by combining distinct upstream routes to erythrose, parallel Shen branches to the imidazole aldehyde (direct formamidine route, glycol dehydration funnel, formaldehyde/ammonia branch through imidazole-4-ethanol, and combined glycol funnels), and two endgame options for aminonitrile formation/hydrolysis: canonical Strecker logic and a more speculative but literature-motivated neutral-pH diamidophosphate-assisted Strecker variant explicitly marked as unvalidated for the histidine substrate. Biochemical-stage reactions are restricted to hydrolysis, stabilization, adsorption, and downstream preservation/compartmentalization rather than unsupported de novo synthesis.\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"CO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_002\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"molecular hydrogen\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_003\",\n      \"formula\": \"CHOO-\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"methanoate\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)/p-1\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"methanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxyethanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c