"role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "azane", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C5H8N2O2", "iupac_name": "2-(1H-imidazol-4-yl)ethane-1,2-diol", "common_name": "imidazole-4-glycol", "inchi": null, "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C5H6N2O", "iupac_name": "2-(1H-imidazol-4-yl)acetaldehyde", "common_name": "imidazole-4-acetaldehyde", "inchi": null, "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C5H8N2O", "iupac_name": "2-(1H-imidazol-4-yl)ethan-1-ol", "common_name": "imidazole-4-ethanol", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C6H7N3", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-(1H-imidazol-4-yl)propanenitrile", "common_name": "histidine aminonitrile", "inchi": null, "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "C6H9N3O2", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-(1H-imidazol-4-yl)propanoic acid", "common_name": "histidine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C6H9N3O2/c7-4(6(10)11)1-5-2-8-3-9-5/h2-4H,1,7H2,(H,8,9)(H,10,11)", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_016", "formula": "CH5N", "iupac_name": "methylamine", "common_name": "methylamine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH5N/c1-2/h2H2,1H3", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_017", "formula": "C3H7N3O3P", "iupac_name": "diamidophosphate", "common_name": "DAP", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_003"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite and mackinawite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline vent conditions; anoxic; H2-rich serpentinization setting"}, "mechanism": "Mineral-surface reduction of CO2 by H2 on Fe-S phases gives reduced C1 species including formate.", "reasoning": "This hydrothermal feeder step is included only as a well-supported vent reaction to connect geochemical carbon fixation into the histidine network; Fe-S-mediated CO2 reduction to formate is consistent with hydrothermal prebiotic chemistry discussed broadly for vent systems, while the histidine report itself emphasizes that histidine requires upstream shared feedstocks from broader prebiotic carbon fixation networks rather than direct meteoritic delivery. The step is used conservatively as a source of reduced carbon feeding surface HCN/sugar systems, not as a histidine-specific claim (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Patel et al., 2015; Shen et al., 1987)."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Hydrothermal Fischer-Tropsch-type generation of formaldehyde-equivalent carbonyl feedstock", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_004"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "elemental iron (Fe0)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "400-500K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite and Fe0", "aqueous": "true", "other": "subseafloor/hydrothermal redox gradients; this connector is a generalized reduced-carbonyl feeder, not a histidine-specific demonstrated step"}, "mechanism": "CO2/H2 hydrogenation on iron oxides and Fe0 generates reduced carbonyl species including formaldehyde-equivalent feedstock that can be exported to surface pools.", "reasoning": "The network avoids the previously criticized unsupported formate-to-HCN step and instead uses a cautious hydrothermal source of simple carbonyl feedstock. Formaldehyde is needed because Shen et al. (1987) explicitly demonstrated an erythrose + formaldehyde + ammonia branch to imidazole-4-ethanol/imidzole-4-glycol, while broader prebiotic carbon fixation literature supports hydrothermal formation of simple reduced organics on magnetite/iron surfaces. This specific mapping to formaldehyde remains less direct than the Shen core and should be regarded as a system-level feeder rather than a histidine-specific validated transformation (Ritson & Sutherland, 2012; Patel et al., 2015; Shen et al., 1987)."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Surface HCN photoredox homologation to glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_009"], "outputs": ["mol_005", "mol_006"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "UV-active mineral surfaces with borate stabilization", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV irradiation; cyanometallate-style HCN photochemistry conceptually represented; borate used here to stabilize emerging sugars in evaporitic pools"}, "mechanism": "HCN-derived photoredox chemistry generates small sugars and sugar precursors, furnishing glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde as shared carbonyl hubs.", "reasoning": "Ritson & Sutherland (2012) demonstrated formation of simple sugars from HCN under UV photochemistry involving cyanometallate systems, and Patel et al. (2015) further established an HCN-centered systems chemistry linking sugar and amino-acid precursor production. Borate stabilization of sugars is a standard surface prebiotic constraint included here to preserve aldehydo sugars in evaporitic environments. Mineral agents are specified per schema, though the key literature catalyst class is cyanometallate photoredox rather than TiO2 itself; this is a surface-environment representation of the documented HCN-to-sugar feeder logic (Ritson & Sutherland, 2012; Patel et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Surface aldol buildup to erythrose", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "borate minerals and montmorillonite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "wet-dry cycling in evaporitic pools; borate stabilization to limit sugar scrambling"}, "mechanism": "Aldol condensation and tetrose assembly from lower sugars yields erythrose, with mineral surfaces concentrating and stabilizing intermediates.", "reasoning": "The histidine literature identifies erythrose as the experimentally demonstrated tetrose input for Shen chemistry and notes that its plausible prebiotic availability must come from upstream sugar-forming networks despite selectivity challenges. This reaction therefore represents the literature-supported systems-level connection from glycolaldehyde/glyceraldehyde to erythrose under sugar-forming surface conditions, with borate invoked to address the recognized instability and unselective nature of prebiotic sugars (Shen et al., 1987; Ritson & Sutherland, 2012; Patel et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "HCN-ammonia conversion to formamidine reservoir", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_010"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "concentration on mineral surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "concentrating microenvironments required; product availability acknowledged as a bottleneck under dilute conditions"}, "mechanism": "HCN/NH3 chemistry in concentrated settings furnishes amidine-like nitrogenous intermediates represented here by formamidine.", "reasoning": "Shen et al. (1987) explicitly treated formamidine as a chemically plausible prebiotic reagent related to HCN-driven purine chemistry while also emphasizing the difficulty of producing it under dilute NH3 + HCN conditions. This node is therefore included as a bottleneck precursor reservoir, not as a high-confidence bulk-environment reaction. Mineral concentration agents are used to reflect the need for local enrichment that the literature identifies as necessary (Shen et al., 1987; Stribling & Miller, 1987)."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Shen condensation: erythrose plus formamidine to imidazole-4-acetaldehyde and imidazole-4-glycol", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_008"], "outputs": ["mol_011", "mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "353K (80C)", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "none established in the original experiment; mineral surfaces included as concentrative supports", "aqueous": "true", "other": "0.03 M erythrose and 0.03 M formamidine; 12 h; yield maximum near pH about 6"}, "mechanism": "Warm near-neutral condensation of a tetrose with formamidine forms imidazole-functionalized side-chain products including imidazole-4-acetaldehyde and imidazole-4-glycol.", "reasoning": "This is the core experimentally demonstrated upstream histidine reaction. Shen et al. (1987) reported imidazole-4-acetaldehyde at 1.6% yield from erythrose + formamidine, and imidazole-4-glycol as a co-product, with optimum around pH approximately 6 and explicit conditions of 0.03 M reactants at 80 C for 12 h. The mineral agents here are not claimed as demonstrated catalysts in the original paper, but are included as plausible surface concentrators to fit the required schema while preserving the exact Shen reaction conditions in the conditions field (Shen et al., 1987)."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Shen alternative branch: erythrose plus formaldehyde plus ammonia to imidazole-4-ethanol and imidazole-4-glycol", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_004", "mol_010"], "outputs": ["mol_013", "mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "353K (80C)", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "none established in the original experiment; mineral surfaces included as concentrative supports", "aqueous": "true", "other": "warm aqueous reaction; related Shen branch producing imidazole-4-ethanol at 5.4% and imidazole-4-glycol at 1.8% relative to erythrose"}, "mechanism": "Carbohydrate-carbonyl-ammonia condensation gives alternative imidazole-bearing alcohol/diol intermediates that funnel toward the key aldehyde.", "reasoning": "Shen et al. (1987) directly reported formation of imidazole-4-ethanol and imidazole-4-glycol from erythrose + formaldehyde + ammonia. This branch is therefore retained, but unlike failed earlier attempts it is not overstated as a complete route by itself; it serves only as a convergent feeder into the experimentally discussed aldehyde funnel. The requirement for formaldehyde availability and the uncertainty of downstream oxidation are acknowledged elsewhere (Shen et al., 1987)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Imidazole-4-glycol dehydration to imidazole-4-acetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_011"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "330-353K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "acidic or drying microenvironments on mineral surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "near-neutral to mildly acidic staged conditions; dehydration proposed rather than directly isolated as a standalone prebiotic experiment"}, "mechanism": "Dehydration of the imidazole diol furnishes the corresponding aldehyde, providing a convergent funnel into the Strecker substrate.", "reasoning": "Shen et al. (1987) explicitly discussed dehydration of imidazole-4-glycol as a plausible route to imidazole-4-acetaldehyde and sketched acid-catalyzed dehydration possibilities. This reaction is therefore literature-motivated but still less directly validated than rxn_006, and is marked as a mechanistic funnel rather than a fully closed experimental step. It is retained because the report itself identifies this interconversion as central to understanding product formation (Shen et al., 1987)."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Imidazole-4-ethanol oxidation/dehydrogenation to imidazole-4-acetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_013"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS2)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "320-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mineral-assisted redox surface", "aqueous": "true", "other": "staged oxidant-poor prebiotic settings; possible oxidants discussed in literature include aldehydes, sulfur, and traces of ferric ion"}, "mechanism": "Mineral-assisted dehydrogenation/oxidation of imidazole-4-ethanol yields the corresponding aldehyde.", "reasoning": "This is an explicitly uncertain but necessary connector that the deep research identifies as an open question rather than a resolved experiment. Shen et al. (1987) note that the oxidizing agent for conversion of related alcohols to the aldehyde is unclear and suggest plausible primitive-Earth oxidants including aldehydes, elemental sulfur, and traces of ferric ion. Here the step is retained as speculative and low-confidence, with mineral surfaces used only to model a geochemical redox setting; it should be treated as a gap-addressing hypothesis rather than established histidine chemistry (Shen et al., 1987)."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Canonical Strecker formation of histidine aminonitrile from imidazole-4-acetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_009", "mol_010"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "none established; concentration on mineral surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "cyanide/ammonia-rich stage separated in time or space from pH~6 aldehyde-forming stage"}, "mechanism": "Imine formation from the aldehyde and ammonia is followed by cyanide addition to give the imidazole-substituted aminonitrile.", "reasoning": "The Shen histidine sequence relies on exactly this Strecker logic from imidazole-4-acetaldehyde using NH3 and HCN. The 1987 paper states the Strecker conversion explicitly, and the 1990 follow-up reports conversion of the aldehyde to histidine without isolating intermediates after adding HCN and ammonia. Because the aminonitrile was not isolated in the key paper, it is represented here as the standard mechanistic intermediate connecting the reported chemistry to final hydrolysis. The literature also notes the pH mismatch between aldehyde formation near pH about 6 and classical Strecker preferences, motivating staged environments rather than a single homogeneous reactor (Shen et al., 1987; Shen et al., 1990; Stribling & Miller, 1987)."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Neutral-pH diamidophosphate-assisted Strecker variant to histidine aminonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_009", "mol_017"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "298-310K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "diamidophosphate in neutral aqueous medium", "aqueous": "true", "other": "optimum conceptually near pH 7 based on modified Strecker chemistry; not validated specifically for imidazole-4-acetaldehyde"}, "mechanism": "Phosphorylation-assisted aminonitrile formation shifts Strecker-type chemistry toward neutral pH, potentially easing incompatibility with Shen aldehyde formation conditions.", "reasoning": "Ashe et al. (2019) showed that aldehydes plus HCN plus diamidophosphate yield N-phosphorylated aminonitriles at neutral pH, contrasting with typical alkaline Strecker conditions. The deep research specifically identifies this as a possible way to reconcile the pH mismatch in histidine networks, but also notes that it has not been demonstrated for imidazole-4-acetaldehyde. Accordingly this branch is retained only as a literature-motivated, explicitly speculative variant and not as a primary validated route (Ashe et al., 2019; Shen et al., 1990)."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Hydrolysis of histidine aminonitrile to histidine", "inputs": ["mol_014"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "geothermal cycling or prolonged aqueous residence; no O2"}, "mechanism": "Sequential nitrile hydration and hydrolysis convert the aminonitrile into the amino acid carboxylate.", "reasoning": "This is the standard completion of Strecker chemistry and is the implicit final step connecting the Shen aldehyde-plus-HCN-plus-ammonia experiment to histidine. Shen et al. (1990) reported histidine detection after adding HCN and ammonia to imidazole-4-acetaldehyde without isolating intermediates; representing aminonitrile hydrolysis as a separate node clarifies the network logic while remaining faithful to standard Strecker chemistry (Shen et al., 1990; Stribling & Miller, 1987)."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "Biochemical adsorption and preservation of histidine on montmorillonite-rich mineral interfaces", "inputs": ["mol_015"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "293-323K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "hours to days; seawater ion composition influences adsorption thermodynamics"}, "mechanism": "Reversible adsorption concentrates and stabilizes histidine on clay-rich mineral interfaces.", "reasoning": "This reaction is included to capture the literature-supported downstream fate of histidine once formed. Samulewski et al. (2021) showed histidine adsorption onto modified montmorillonite with multi-phase kinetics and thermodynamic shifts toward favorable adsorption over longer times, indicating a plausible concentration/preservation mechanism in prebiotic pools. This is not a synthetic step but is relevant for network continuity and survivability (Samulewski et al., 2021)."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Canonical Shen histidine route from HCN-derived erythrose", "description": "HCN photochemistry furnishes glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde, aldol chemistry gives erythrose, concentrated HCN/NH3 chemistry supplies formamidine, Shen condensation forms imidazole-4-acetaldehyde directly, and canonical Strecker/hydrolysis yields histidine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_010", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_012", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "Shen glycol-funnel route", "description": "As in the canonical route, but the productive branch proceeds through imidazole-4-glycol, which dehydrates to the aldehyde before Strecker conversion.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_008", "rxn_010", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_011", "mol_012", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P3", "name": "Formaldehyde-assisted Shen branch via imidazole-4-ethanol", "description": "HCN-derived erythrose combines with formaldehyde and ammonia to form imidazole-4-ethanol, which is then oxidized to imidazole-4-acetaldehyde before the standard Strecker finish.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_002", "rxn_007", "rxn_009", "rxn_010", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_013", "mol_012", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P4", "name": "Formaldehyde-assisted Shen branch via glycol dehydration", "description": "The erythrose plus formaldehyde plus ammonia branch generates imidazole-4-glycol, which dehydrates to the key aldehyde and then enters the canonical Strecker route.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_002", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_010", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_011", "mol_012", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P5", "name": "Hydrothermal-formate-fed canonical Shen route", "description": "Hydrothermal CO2 reduction supplies reduced carbon to surface HCN-centered chemistry; surface sugar assembly and formamidine generation then follow the canonical Shen route to histidine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_010", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_003", "mol_007", "mol_012", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P6", "name": "Hydrothermal-formate-fed glycol-funnel Shen route", "description": "Hydrothermal reduced carbon feeds surface HCN photochemistry; erythrose and formamidine produce imidazole-4-glycol, which dehydrates to the Strecker substrate and then histidine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_008", "rxn_010", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_003", "mol_011", "mol_012", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P7", "name": "Canonical Shen route with biochemical preservation", "description": "The validated Shen route yields histidine, which is then concentrated and preserved on montmorillonite-rich mineral interfaces.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_010", "rxn_012", "rxn_013"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_012", "mol_014", "mol_015"]}, {"pathway_id": "P8", "name": "Glycol-funnel Shen route with biochemical preservation", "description": "The imidazole-4-glycol branch feeds the aldehyde, then canonical Strecker/hydrolysis forms histidine, which is subsequently adsorbed and stabilized on clay.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_008", "rxn_010", "rxn_012", "rxn_013"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_011", "mol_012", "mol_015"]}, {"pathway_id": "P9", "name": "Neutral-pH diamidophosphate-assisted histidine route", "description": "The Shen aldehyde is produced directly from erythrose plus formamidine, but the endgame uses a neutral-pH DAP-assisted Strecker variant before hydrolysis to histidine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_011", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_012", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P1